<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-16T00:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-16T00:36:00-05:00" n="686" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d686">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/11988.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Admiral <persName type="from">Fletcher</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of the Navy</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">Florida, <lb/> Vera
                                    Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-15T23:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 15, 1914, 11 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>On April 14, in answer to specific questions, have obtained from Mayo
                            following answers: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>Our boats daily used regular landing during attack [of
                                    Constitutionalists] on Tampico, without objection previous to
                                    the arrest. No notice that other landings were forbidden had
                                    been given. We were never requested to give notice nor obtain
                                    permission before landing boats’ crews. I received no notice
                                    that hostilities existed. The only restriction imposed upon our
                                    movements was a refusal to pass through the [Federal] lines to
                                    deliver letter to Rebels. I will also transmit the foregoing to
                                    the American Embassy. Foreign warships report same
                                    conditions.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Fletcher</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>